dspace.title: REQ0134447 - Continuous 503 Service Unavailable messages for the OAR (https://oar.princeton.edu/jspui/mydspace)

comments.body: Thank you for notifying us, I'm tracking this in https://princeton.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=sc_req_item.do?sys_id=800e1d62db184454a4f72736059619cc.  This was apparently an issue in the past, and I don't wish to lose any of the history captured on that ticket.

Because this seems to only affect authenticated users (and I cannot reproduce it from my personal account), I'm going to proceed with addressing https://github.com/pulibrary/dspace/issues/4.  Perhaps using a separate account will prevent these errors from occurring (at least, until a proper solution is identified).

Reindexing for DataSpace appears to have updated a number of collections, but I'm not quite sure that this resolved the problem.  I'm trying to reindex the installation once again and capturing the logs for review (thus far items indexed [e. g. https://dataspace.princeton.edu/jspui/handle/88435/dsp018s45q877p are properly discoverable: https://dataspace.princeton.edu/jspui/simple-search?location=%2F&query=Using+the+Longitudinal+Structure+of+Earnings+to+Estimate+the+Effect+of+Training+Programs&rpp=10&sort_by=score&order=desc)]

This was indeed a Solr indexing failure, and was resolved by manually updating the index (see https://dataspace.princeton.edu/jspui/handle/88435/dsp01zw12z8154?mode=full and https://dataspace.princeton.edu/jspui/handle/88435/dsp01br86b597x).  Why this is not automatically run by a `cron` job needs to be identified before this is closed.

@escowles , @kevinreiss  and I will be working on this next week

This ticket proposes to preserve "everything", but that is a little misleading. A few thoughts...

- We should not preserve resource types that are only nested within other resources. Correct?
- The existing preservation logic only preserves resources that are "complete"., however there are a number of resource types without a state property. We will need to change the logic for these. I assume it's preserve on save when there is no state.
- There are handful of resources that I don't know if we should preserve or not (see below). 

Resource | Preserve | Has State Property
-- | -- | --
Collection | Y | Y
DateRange | N | N
EphemeraBox | Y | Y
EphemeraField | Y | N
EphemeraFolder | Y | Y
EphemeraProject | Y | N
EphemeraTerm | Y | N
EphemeraVocabularies | Y | N
Event |   | N
FileSet |   | N
MediaResource | Y | Y
NameWithPlace | N | N
NestedResource | N | N
NumismaticAccession | Y | N
NumismaticArtist | N | N
NumismaticAttribute | N | N
NumismaticCitation | N | N
NumismaticCoin | Y | Y
NumismaticFind | N | N
NumismaticFirm | Y | N
NumismaticIssue | Y | Y
NumismaticLoan | N | N
NumismaticMonogram | Y | N
NumismaticNote | N | N
NumismaticPerson | Y | N
NumismaticPlace | Y | N
NumismaticProvenance | N | N
NumismaticReference | Y | N
NumismaticSubject | N | N
PreservationObject |   | N
ProxyFileSet |   | N
RasterResource | Y | Y
ScannedMap | Y | Y
ScannedResource | Y | Y
Template | Y | N
Tombstone |   | N
VectorResource | Y | Y
WorkflowNote | N | N

@eliotjordan I think it might make sense to break down by a couple of different categories of resources:
1. "Works" and collections, e.g., ArchivalMediaCollection, Collection, EphemeraBox, EphemeraFolder, MediaResource, NumismaticCoin, NumismaticIssue, Recording, ScannedMap, ScannedResource, and VectorResource. The most convenient way to identify these is the resources with a state property, where we can preserve them when they are complete.
2. Nested resources — I assume these are never preserved because they are preserved in their parent resources.
3. Helper resources, e.g., most of the numismatic, ephemera, and controlled vocab fields, which should be preserved on every save.
4. The preservation machinery itself, like Event, PreservationObject, Tombstone. I don't know if these need to be preserved (maybe they need to be preserved so we can access historical versions if we do a complete restore?) — but there may be complications in preserving them and preventing recursive preservation processes.
5. FileSet is probably a special case — needs to be preserved, but only as part of a parent "work".
Regarding 2., nested resources are preserved individually - it's just that their test for "should I be preserved" is "does my parent say it's preserved"

comments.body:
In order to address `sed`-like operations one is faced with two options:
- https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/modules/replace_module.html#replace-module
- https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/modules/shell_module.html?highlight=shell

There may be some limitations to using `replace`, but it seems to provide enough support for RegExp that this could suffice for porting the `sed` operations found in the Vagrantfile.

The Ansible documentation on variables can be found here: https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/user_guide/playbooks_variables.html

Specifically, the variable precedence follows this scheme:

- command line values (eg “-u user”)
- `role` defaults
- inventory file or script group vars
- inventory `group_vars/all`
- playbook `group_vars/all`
- inventory `group_vars/*`
- playbook `group_vars/*`
- inventory file or script host vars
- inventory `host_vars/*`
- playbook `host_vars/*`
- host facts / cached set_facts
- play `vars`
- play `vars_prompt`
- play `vars_files`
- role vars (defined in `role/vars/main.yml`)
- block vars (only for tasks in block)
- task vars (only for the task)
- include_vars
- set_facts / registered vars
- role (and include_role) params
- include params
- extra vars (always win precedence)

(please see the section https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/user_guide/playbooks_variables.html#variable-precedence-where-should-i-put-a-variable)
